Ok after scrapping all my preconceptions and creating a gradle prototype I&#39;ve found a working solution. This is what I&#39;ve done:

First I&#39;ve added a new property to gradle.properties **mode=dist**&lt;br&gt;
This enabled me to split my dependencies via **if(mode == &quot;dist&quot;)** and the **else** blocks. As an exmpale:
```
dependencies {
  if (mode == &quot;dist&quot;){
    implementation &quot;com.example:Connector:1.0.0:api&quot; 
  } else {
    implementation &quot;com.example:Connector-bundle:1.0.0&quot;
  }
}
```

Thanks to this setup, gradle by default now acts as if I&#39;m in distribution mode, meaning I always load the API library, not the full thing.

Next I&#39;ve created a custom task **publishBundle** where I set **mode = &quot;lib&quot;** and do the whole build and publish process. As an example:

```
task publishBundle {
  mode = &quot;lib&quot;
  dependsOn &quot;build&quot;
  dependsOn &quot;publishBundlePublicationToNexusRepository&quot;
}
```

The last adjustment had to happen in the publishing configuration. Here I had to add the correct mode values too:

```
  publishing {
    publications {
      dist(MavenPublication) {
        mode = &quot;dist&quot;
        alias false
        from components.java
        afterEvaluate {
          artifact apiJar
        }
      }
      bundle(MavenPublication) {
        mode = &quot;lib&quot;
        alias true
        from components.java
        afterEvaluate {
          artifactId &quot;${artifactId}-bundle&quot;
        }
      }
    }
    repositories {...}
  }
```

With this, the normal build and publish process will follow the distributed approach, while the **publishBundle** task creates and publishes the bundles. In our repository we now have two connector projects: connector and connector-bundle, meaning we can handle the different dependencies depending on the mode we&#39;re in.

It still feels like a patchwork, but I can imagine that my requirements are just too... special.

